Rating: 4
Very easy to make. I'm starting my second one this week. It's like eating the best part of pecan pie, not too gooey and sweet...just right! I like the maple syrup instead of corn syrup too.

Rating: 4
This has a huge return on investment: very simple effort that returns a pretty and delicious result. I made it the original way and it was a huge hit. Risking gilding the lily, when I made it a second time I added a layer of bittersweet chocolate chips before pouring in the walnut mixture. I don't think I'll ever make it w/o the chocolate again!

Rating: 3
Very delicious! I quadrupled the filling recipe to make this into a deep dish 9" pie with very good success. (Used the Foolproof Pie Crust recipe from The Best of America's Test Kitchen 2009 book I recently got. Highly recommend it.) I partially pre-baked the pastry (blind baking it filled with pie weights). Made the filling ingredients as instructed (x4) with the minor addition of a few TBL of Kahlua. Very tasty indeed. Before pouring the fillng into the crust, (and after blind baking it - duh) I added a thick layer of high quality bittersweet coarsely chopped chocolate. Then poured the crust over and baked as directed. I had to tent the pie with foil for the last 10 minutes, as the walnuts were darkening, but it came out looking rustic and gorgeous. I took this to a potluck dinner party - got raves. One friend, who claims to hate pecan pie b/c of its cloying sweetness, loved it - eyes rolling to the back of his head and a big: "mmmmm!" Great with vanilla icea cream or whipped cream.

Rating: 4
So simple and so delicious! We tried it with both lightly sweetened whipped cream or vanilla ice cream and everyone agreed - ice cream is a much better accompaniment.

Rating: 3
A quick and attractive tart, and great to use only one container for the filling! I had no corn syrup so added an extra 1/4 cup brown sugar and 1/2 cup water and it still worked well. Next time I'll line the pastry with dark chocolate to add some depth to the flavour.

